post_text:
On August 31, 2020 the USDA issued a press release stating they are extending free meals until December 31, 2020 or until the funds appropriated by Congress are exhausted. These meals will be free to students enrolled at the Attica Central School District.

In the event the free emergency meal program ends, we will go back to a Free, Reduced and Full Pay status using meal applications which can be found on our website, therefore, it is imperative that the district has the application on file no later than September 30th, 2020, regardless of enrollment status (i.e., hybrid or 100% remote learning). If you have any questions, please contact Kris Wicks, Food Service Director at (585)591-0400, ext. 1195.

We are pleased to announce that the Attica Faculty Association will have a booth at the Harding's Craft Fair on July 11-12th. They will be giving out free books to children, and will be conducting a food drive to benefit several of the food banks that our students and community members use. If possible, please bring at least one item (canned, boxed, toiletry, or monetary) to contribute!

ALSO - the AFA will match any monetary donations (up to $1,000) collected during the food drive!

post_text: The Attica FFA was recently selected as one of four local chapters to participate in a cheese donation through the Butterfly Foundation's "Say Cheese" program. We received over 450 pounds of cheese from Yancey's Fancy that was then distributed to our community through the Attica CSD lunch program and the Attica Food Pantry. We are so grateful for the work of Jeff Durkin and George Jarett of the Butterfly Foundation, as well as Bob Kozlowski and Matt Lamb for making this project possible. As always, the staff at Attica CSD did an amazing job adding the cheese to over 800 school lunches that go out several times each week. The Attica FFA is excited that they were able to support NYS dairy producers and processors in this challenging time. Thank you to all who helped make this project a possibility!

We are so grateful for the work of Jeff Durkin and George Jarett of the Butterfly Foundation, as well as Bob Kozlowski and Matt Lamb for making this project possible. As always, the staff at Attica CSD did an amazing job adding the cheese to over 800 school lunches that go out several times each week. The Attica FFA is excited that they were able to support NYS dairy producers and processors in this challenging time. Thank you to all who helped make this project a possibility!

For all Middle School and High School students:
Please remember that any work that was assigned PRIOR to March 12 is due by May 18. After May 18, no work that was assigned prior to the school closure will be accepted.

For students in grades k-12:
Any work that has been assigned in packets during the closure is due by June 5, and can be turned in at the main office of the respective school building from 8:00 am to 3:00 pm Monday-Friday, or electronically directly to your teachers. You do not need to wait until June 5 to turn it in, but all work must be turned in by June 5.

Instructional Material Pickup Schedule

post_text:
A note from Mr. Clark:

Middle School will begin pick-up times for academic packets tomorrow, March 19th from 9:00 AM-3:00 PM and 5:00 PM-7:00 PM, as well as Friday, March 20th from 9:00 AM-3:00 PM only. You can pick up curbside near the Middle School entrance. Staff will ask who you are picking up for and deliver to your car. There will be a paper packet for every student as well as academic websites to visit for review and practice. If you have questions regarding a specific subject, feel free to email your respective teacher. Remember this material is not made to stress you out or cause anxiety. We only ask that you try your best and attempt what you can. Mr. Clark is also available for questions via phone 591-0400 ext. 1500 or email pclark2@atticacsd.org. Keep in mind that your safety is the utmost priority, so stay safe and stay positive.
Thank you!

Pictured Back Row (left to right) Aurora Orlowski, Hannah Royce, Hailie Pfaff-Snyder, Stephanie Silvernail, Zakry Howard, Aric Schosek,

Front Row (left to right): Alanna Pellicane, Rebekah Clark, Mia Mondano, Konner Rippel

The Attica Central School district is now offering access to the Safe School Hotline, a 24 hour confidential reporting service to report concerns about unsafe or potentially disruptive activities or situations, drug or alcohol use, weapons, harassment, bullying, threats, possible suicide, or any other safety issue.

The Safe School Hotline can be accessed via the following methods:
- Call 1-800-4-1-VOICE ext. 359 (1-800-418-6423 ext. 259)
- Visit www.safeschoolhelpline.com or
facebook.com/safeschoolhelpline
- Text TIPS to 66746
- Download the "Safe School Helpline" app.

See the documents below for more information!

post_text: Congratulations to Kathryn Metzger for being accepted to Jr. High Area All State orchestra. Jr High Area All State was held on November 1 and 2 at Greece Athena School. The concert Was November 2, 2019 at 2:90pm. Performances included the following groups: Band, Choral, and orchestra. The orchestra was conducted by Lynne Ruda and performed the Egyptian Legacy arranged by S. Newbold, Farandole From L’Arlesienne arranged by D. Stone, and The Lord of the Dance arranged by L. Moore. The orchestra is composed of many different students across the region from the following counties: Orleans, Genesee, Wyoming, Monroe, Livingston, Ontario.

Congratulations to Mr. Alex Burks, our 8th grade science teacher here in the Middle School.

This past weekend he ran in his first marathon, the Corning Glass Marathon. He took home first place with a time of 2 hours and 23 minutes!! On May 28th, SmartSocial will be hosting a free online training for parents and students with screen time tips for iPhone, Android, Xbox, Playstation, and Switch. During the 30 minute training they will cover:

-Why parents should consider setting up parental controls on
their child’s favorite devices
-How to work WITH your kids to set screen time expectations
-How to set parental controls on iPhones and iPads
-How to set parental controls on Android devices (step-by-step
guide)
-How to set parental controls on Xbox (step-by-step guide)
-How to set parental controls on PlayStation (step-by-step
guide)
-How to set parental controls on Switch (step-by-step guide)

Over the last two months, several of our Middle School students have been participating in a STEM/Agriculture Challenge, coordinated through Cornell University and the Wilson Foundation. This weekend the students presented their final proposal - and took first place - beating teams from several other counties in Western New York. Congratulations!!

Any 7th or 8th grade students that are interested in participating in the next session, which will look at biosecurity and agrosecurity, please speak to your science teacher!!

We would like to share the following opportunity!!

On behalf of the Wyoming County Dairy Princess program, could you please announce that the program
is currently looking for candidates to run for the 2019 Dairy Court.

Ages are: 7-9 Dairy Maids, 10-14 Dairy Ambassadors, and 15 and up Alternate/Princess.

The Pageant will be held on Sun., May 5, 2019, at the East Hill Creamery in Perry.

If any girl is interested in helping promote the dairy industry for Wyoming County they may contact Michelle Klein at 585-237-6795 and she will be happy to email you an application. The deadline for applications is Monday, April 8, 2019.

Thank you and Have a Moo-good day,

Big Congratulations to the 7/8 Math Team for finishing in first place overall. After three meets the team had a total of 343 points which was nearly 40 points better than second place!

On top of the team first place finish Attica also took home two outstanding individual honors. Jonah Clark was the highest point scorer overall for all students and Olivia Bernacki was the top scoring 7th grader.

The team also consisted of 8th graders Libby Kibler, Natalie Janes, Cassidy Shafer, Megan Fialkowski, and Hannah Bourgeois. Other 7th grade students were Cash Domes, Samantha Alfiero, Kathryn Metzger, and Aurora Orlowski.

Congratulations!

post_text:
Yesterday the 7/8 Math Team competed at Genesee Community College for the second time this year. The team finished in first place out of 8 teams with a total of 106 points!!

Jonah Clark led the way with a whopping 20 points, 3 more than any other competitor. Olivia Bernacki scored 15 points while Libby Kibler and Cassidy Shafer each had 14. Other members of the team with strong performances were Cash Domes, Aurora Orlowski, Megan Fialkawski, Samantha Alfiero, Hannah Bourgeois, and Kate Metzger.

After two competitions the team is in first place with only one competition left. Also after two competitions Jonah Clark is the overall leader in scoring and Olivia Bernacki is the top scoring 7th Grader.

Great job, everyone!!
